# Caddy reverse proxy for the app, with automatic HTTPS (Let's Encrypt) for your domain.
# The app the agent builds binds to 127.0.0.1:3000; Caddy fronts it on your domain and terminates
# TLS. The bot itself needs none of this — it talks to Telegram outbound — so Caddy is only for
# publishing the app.
#
# Usage:
#   1. Point your domain's DNS A/AAAA record at this host.
#   2. Install Caddy (https://caddyserver.com/docs/install), e.g. on Debian/Ubuntu via the apt repo.
#   3. Set your domain and run it:
#        sudo LILA_DOMAIN=app.example.com caddy run --config deploy/Caddyfile
#      (or copy to /etc/caddy/Caddyfile and `sudo systemctl enable --now caddy`).
#
# Access control is the app's job: generate Rails' built-in auth (bin/rails generate authentication)
# so only you + invited users get in. Caddy just publishes; it does not authenticate.
{$LILA_DOMAIN:localhost} {
	reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:3000
}
